<paper id="1755042603"><title>Provably Secure Implicit Certificate Schemes</title><year>2002</year><authors><author org="Certicom Research" id="2251884570">Daniel R. L. Brown</author><author org="Certicom Research" id="1895790187">Robert P. Gallant</author><author org="University of Waterloo" id="2437791765">Scott A. Vanstone</author></authors><n_citation>57</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1487958904</reference><reference>1592109266</reference><reference>1660562555</reference><reference>1937880336</reference><reference>2002930326</reference><reference>2052267638</reference><reference>2052667569</reference><reference>2080302839</reference><reference>2095708839</reference><reference>2166462813</reference><reference>2169194339</reference></references><venue id="2606870472" type="C">Financial Cryptography</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-46088-8_15</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.41583">Internet privacy</keyword><keyword weight="0.65838">Revocation list</keyword><keyword weight="0.50756">Authentication</keyword><keyword weight="0.66958">X.509</keyword><keyword weight="0.44461">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.44227">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.66635">Certificate authority</keyword><keyword weight="0.52933">Digital signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.64579">Implicit certificate</keyword><keyword weight="0.49347">Provable security</keyword><keyword weight="0.52615">Certificate</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Optimal mail certificates, introduced in [12], are efficient types of implicit certificates which offer many advantages over traditional (explicit) certificates. For example, an optimal mail certificate is small enough to fit on a two-dimensional digital postal mark together with a digital signature. This paper defines a general notion of security for implicit certificates, and proves that optimal mail certificates are secure under this definition.</abstract><